            <p>
                In this lesson, we will look at the equations for calculating the amount of energy in
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="Kinetic energy meant the energy something has when it moves - like a human running.">
                    Kinetic
                </a>
                energy and
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="Gravitational potential energy is the energy something has when above the Earth's surface
                   - like an apple hanging from a tree.">
                    Gravitational potential
                </a>
                energy stores of an object.
            </p>
            <p>In each equation, every effort has been made to break down the equation into its smallest components.</p>
            <p>A worked example is given for each, and a practice example is also available.</p>
            <p>
                Take your mind back to the algebra opening - each symbol is just a placeholder for a number.
