        <!-- PART 1 -->
        <div class="tab-pane fade" id="part1">
            <br />
            <p><strong>Kinetic energy</strong></p>
            <br />
            <p>
                To calculate an object's Kinetic energy, we need to look at the components of an object in motion.
            </p>
            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3">
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <figure style="margin-bottom:0em">
                            <img src="~/images/topics/energy/lesson3/giphy.gif" alt="Car on a road" />
                            <figcaption>Taken from https://giphy.com/gifs/82nxC17BUZwJ8XHXBa/html5</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>
                <strong>Mass.</strong> All objects have
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="Often confused with weight, mass is how much matter something is made up of.">
                    mass
                </a>
                which is measured in
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="This is the standard unit for measuring mass. A kilogram is 1000 grams and often abbreviated
                   to kg.">
                    kilograms
                </a>
                (kg). From your experience of driving a car, you may know that the more weight you put in the car, the
                harder you have to get the engine to work to get the car to move. The lighter the car is, the less work
                the engine has to do. This means more energy is needed to move a car with a higher mass.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Speed.</strong> An object that is moving has a
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="We normally use miles per hour, or a unit of distance per a unit of time. In physics, we use
                   metres per second. Any reference to miles per hour will also be provided in metres per second for
                   the equations, but you can simply Google a conversion calculator.">
                    speed
                </a>
                at which it is travelling. If you wanted to walk faster, you would need to use more energy and running
                would use even more energy than walking. To move slower would require less energy and standing still
                would use a negligible amount of energy.
            </p>
            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">Kinetic Energy</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E<sub>k</sub> = ½mv<sup>2</sup></h1>
                        <p class="card-text"><u><b>Where;</b></u></p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>E<sub>k</b> is the Kinetic Energy store measured in joules</p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>½</b> is a half of 1, normally put in a calculator as 0.5</p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>m</b> is the mass of an object measured in kilograms (kg)</p>
                        <p class="card-text">
                            <b>v<sup>2</sup></b> is the speed of the object in metres per second,
                            but it has been
                            <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                               title="To square a number is to multiply it by itself.">
                                squared
                            </a>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PART 2 -->
        <div class="tab-pane fade" id="part2">
            <br />
            <p>
                When we combine the two components (mass and speed) together, it's easy to imagine moving something
                heavy at a high speed requires a lot of energy, and something with very little mass at a high speed
                requires a lot less energy.
            </p>
            <p>We can show this mathematically.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    The average weight of a midsize car in the UK is 1600 kilograms (1.6 tons). We will keep the mass the same
                    and change the value of speed to compare the differences in the kinetic energy of an object.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Whilst it's stationary (0 metres per second), it would have no kinetic energy because anything multiplied
                    by zero is still zero.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The speed limit in a UK town is 30 mph (13 metres per second).
                </li>
                <li>
                    The speed limit on a UK motorway is 70 mph (31 metres per second).
                </li>
                <li>
                    The speed for an instant ban is in excess of 100 mph (45 metres per second).
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>We will now put these numbers into the equation with an explanation below.</p>

            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">30 miles per hour</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E<sub>k</sub> = ½mv<sup>2</sup></h1>
                        <p class="card-text">We need to change the m and the v to the relevant numbers from the text above.</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Mass = 1600 kilograms </p>
                        <p class="card-text">Speed = 30 miles per hour <strong>or</strong> 13 metres per second<sup>2</sup></p>
                        <p class="card-text">
                            It's worth working out the squared before putting it into the equation, so
                            13 x 13 = 169
                        </p>
                        <p>E<sub>k </sub>= 0.5 x 1600 x 169</p>
                        <p>E<sub>k </sub>= 135,200 joules of energy
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>


            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">70 miles per hour</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E<sub>k</sub> = ½mv<sup>2</sup></h1>
                        <p class="card-text">We will keep m the same but v is now increased from 30mph to 70mph.</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Mass = 1600 kilograms </p>
                        <p class="card-text">Speed = 70 miles per hour <strong>or</strong> 31 metres per second<sup>2</sup></p>
                        <p class="card-text">
                            It's worth working out the squared before putting it into the equation, so
                            31 x 31 = 961
                        </p>
                        <p>E<sub>k </sub>= 0.5 x 1600 x 961</p>
                        <p>E<sub>k </sub>= 768,800 joules of energy
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">100 miles per hour</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E<sub>k </sub>= ½mv<sup>2</sup></h1>
                        <p class="card-text">The m still stays the same but v is now increased from 70mph to 100mph.</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Mass = 1600 kilograms </p>
                        <p class="card-text">Speed = 100 miles per hour <strong>or</strong> 45 metres per second<sup>2</sup></p>
                        <p class="card-text">
                            It's worth working out the squared before putting it into the equation, so
                            45 x 45 = 2,025
                        </p>
                        <p>E<sub>k </sub>= 0.5 x 1600 x 2,025</p>
                        <p>E<sub>k </sub>= 1,620,000 joules of energy
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>
                <strong>Conclusion.</strong> So from the results, you can see mathematically
            </p>
        </div>

