        <!-- PART 4 -->
        <div class="tab-pane fade" id="part4">
            <br />
            <p><strong>Gravitational potential energy</strong></p>
            <br />
            <p>
                To calculate an object's gravitational potential energy (or G.P.E.), we need to look at objects in the air.
            </p>
            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3">
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <figure style="margin-bottom:0em">
                            <img src="~/images/topics/energy/lesson3/aerial-airforce-army-38523.jpg" alt="Skydiving" />
                            <figcaption>Photo by Pixabay from Pexels
                        </figure>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>
                <strong>Mass.</strong> Just like kinetic energy, the objects we look at have
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="Often confused with weight, mass is how much matter something is made up of.">
                    mass
                </a>
                which is measured in
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="This is the standard unit for measuring mass. A kilogram is 1000 grams and often abbreviated
                   to kg.">
                    kilograms
                </a>
                (kg). There's a common misconception that a heavy object falls faster than a light object - a heavy object
                certainly has more G.P.E. than a light energy. In reality, everything falls at the same rate and therefore
                we don't need to use speed in this equation, just mass.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Height.</strong> This is an obviously important factor - the higher an object has to fall, the more
                energy it is going to have in it's G.P.E. store. Height is measured in metre's, and this is measured from
                the Earth's surface.
            </p>
            <p>
                <strong>Gravitational field strength.</strong> The Earth (and other large celestial bodies) all have a
                gravitational field, within which a force exists that pulls objects towards it. Gravity on Earth is a
                <a href="javascript://" style="color:black; font-weight:bold;" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="top"
                   title="A constant is as it sounds - constant. This means a number that we can use and it shouldn't change.">
                    constant
                </a>. The Earth's gravitational field strength is 9.81 N/kg, which means for every kilogram of an object's mass, it
                has a force of 9.81 Newtons pulling it to the ground. This is approximately the force required to hold up a
                10kg dumb bell a metre in the air.
            </p>
            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">Gravitational Potential Energy</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E<sub>g</sub> = mgh</h1>
                        <p class="card-text"><u><b>Where;</b></u></p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>E<sub>g</sub></b> is the G.P.E. store measured in joules</p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>m</b> is the mass of an object measured in kilograms (kg)</p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>g</b> is the gravitational field strength of the Earth (9.81), measured in N/kg</p>
                        <p class="card-text"><b>h</b> is the height above the Earth's surface measured in metres (m)</p>
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- PART 5 -->
        <div class="tab-pane fade" id="part5">
            <br />
            <p>
                When we combine the three components (mass, gravitational field strength and height) together, it's easy to
                imagine that the higher you climb, for example up a tree or a building, the the harder your fall would be.
            </p>
            <p>We can again show this mathematically.</p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    The average weight of a man in the UK is 85kg, and we know the Earth's gravitational strength is 9.81 N/kg.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Let's imagine a man standing in a tree at 5 metres height.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Secondly we'll compare that to the G.P.E. of the same man standing on Big Ben at approximately 100 metres (96...)
                </li>
                <li>
                    Lastly, we can take Big Ben (~100 metres) to the Moon and see what the difference would be up there.
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>We will now put these numbers into the equation with an explanation below.</p>

            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">A man up a tree</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E = m x g x h</h1>
                        <p class="card-text">We need to change the m and the g to the relevant numbers from the text above.</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Mass = 85 kilograms </p>
                        <p class="card-text">Gravitational field strength = 9.81 N/kg</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Height = 5 metre </p>
                        <p>E<sub>g</sub> = 85 x 9.81 x 5</p>
                        <p>E<sub>g</sub> = 833.85 joules of energy
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">A man on Big Ben</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E = m x g x h</h1>
                        <p class="card-text">We will keep m and g the same as before.</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Mass = 85 kilograms </p>
                        <p class="card-text">Gravitational field strength = 9.81 N/kg</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Height = 100 metres </p>
                        <p>E<sub>g</sub> = 85 x 9.81 x 100</p>
                        <p>E<sub>g</sub> = 83,385 joules of energy
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <p>
                So from these results, the same mass dropped on Earth increases in energy based upon it's height above the Earth's
                surface. To demonstrate this, there is one final worked example below of an average man at 100 metres height above
                the Moon. See below.
            </p>
            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3">
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <figure style="margin-bottom:0em">
                            <img src="~/images/topics/energy/lesson3/earthmoon.png" alt="Earth and Moon" />
                            <figcaption>Taken from https://www.universetoday.com/20489/moon-compared-to-earth/
                        </figure>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>
                The Moon is a lot smaller than Earth - it has a smaller mass. While the gravitational field strength of Earth is
                9.81 N/kg, the Moon is a lot less at 1.6 N/kg. Jupiter however is so large, it has a gravitational field strength
                two and a half times of Earth at 25 N/kg. After working out the Moon, you can apply the same method to that of
                Jupiter if you wish.
            </p>

            <div class="row justify-content-center">
                <div class="card bg-light mb-3" style="max-width: 60rem;">
                    <div class="card-header">A man on Big Ben, on the Moon</div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h1 class="card-title">E = m x g x h</h1>
                        <p class="card-text">We will keep m and g the same as before.</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Mass = 85 kilograms </p>
                        <p class="card-text">Gravitational field strength = 1.6 N/kg</p>
                        <p class="card-text">Height = 100 metres </p>
                        <p>E<sub>g</sub> = 85 x 1.6 x 100</p>
                        <p>E<sub>g</sub> = 13,600 joules of energy
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

